# Function to detect outliers using IQR
def find_outliers_iqr(df):
    outliers_iqr = {}
    
    for col in df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns:
        Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Find outliers
        outliers = df[(df[col] < lower_bound) | (df[col] > upper_bound)]
        outliers_iqr[col] = outliers.index.tolist()
    
    return outliers_iqr

# Function to detect outliers using Z-score
def find_outliers_z(df, threshold=3):
    df_zscore = df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).apply(zscore)
    
    # Identify outliers (absolute z-score > threshold)
    outliers_z = {col: df[df_zscore[col].abs() > threshold].index.tolist()
                  for col in df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns}
    
    return outliers_z

# Get outliers from both methods
outliers_iqr = find_outliers_iqr(df)
outliers_z = find_outliers_z(df)

# Compare and find differences
for col in df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns:
    iqr_set = set(outliers_iqr[col])
    z_set = set(outliers_z[col])

    print(f"\n**Column: {col}**")
    print(f" Outliers (IQR Method): {len(iqr_set)}")
    print(f" Outliers (Z-score Method): {len(z_set)}")
    print(f" Outliers Found by IQR but Not Z-score: {iqr_set - z_set}")
    print(f" Outliers Found by Z-score but Not IQR: {z_set - iqr_set}")

# Visualize using Boxplot

import pandas as pd

# Define a function to detect outliers using IQR
def detect_outliers_iqr(df):
    outlier_rows = pd.DataFrame()
    
    for col in df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns:  # Select only numerical columns
        Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
        
        # Filter outliers
        outliers = df[(df[col] < lower_bound) | (df[col] > upper_bound)]
        
        if not outliers.empty:
            outliers['Outlier_Column'] = col  # Mark which column had outliers
            outlier_rows = pd.concat([outlier_rows, outliers])
    
    return outlier_rows

# Get outliers in DataFrame format
outliers_df = detect_outliers_iqr(df)
print(outliers_df)

# Loop over the numeric columns to create a stacked bar chart
numeric_columns = ['NumCompaniesWorked', 'PerformanceRating', 'StockOptionLevel',
                    'TotalWorkingYears', 'TrainingTimesLastYear', 'YearsAtCompany',
                    'YearsInCurrentRole', 'YearsSinceLastPromotion', 'YearsWithCurrManager']

# Create a figure for the plot
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=len(numeric_columns), figsize=(15, 6))

for i, col in enumerate(numeric_columns):
    ax = axes[i]
    
    # Group by 'Attribution' and sum the numeric columns
    grouped = df.groupby('Attrition').agg({col: 'sum'}).reset_index()
    
    # Plot the stacked bar chart for this column
    ax.bar(grouped['Attrition'], grouped[col], label=col, color='skyblue')

    # Set the title and labels
    ax.set_title(f'Stacked Bar Chart for {col}')
    ax.set_xlabel('Attrition')
    ax.set_ylabel(f'{col} Values')
    
    ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Loop through each categorical column and plot stacked bar charts
for col in categorical_columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))  # Create a new figure for each plot
    
    # Group by main column and selected categorical column
    category_counts = df.groupby(['Attrition', col]).size().unstack()
    
    # Plot stacked bar chart
    category_counts.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=plt.gca())
    
    # Labels & Title
    plt.xlabel('Attrition')
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.title(f"Stacked Bar Chart: {col} vs {'Attrition'}")
    plt.legend(title=col)
    
    # Show plot
    plt.show()

# Loop through categorical columns
for col in categorical_columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))  # New figure for each plot

    # Group and count occurrences
    category_counts = df.groupby(['Attrition', col]).size().unstack()

    # **Sort columns by total count (sum over rows) in ascending order**
    category_counts = category_counts[category_counts.sum(axis=0).sort_values(ascending=True).index]

    # Plot stacked bar chart
    category_counts.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=plt.gca())

    # Labels & Title
    plt.xlabel('Attrition')
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.title(f"Stacked Bar Chart: {col} vs {'Attrition'}")
    plt.legend(title=col)

    # Show plot
    plt.show()
